docs.abstract: After pleading guilty to tax fraud, Mr. Grimm gave up his seat in 2014. Now he’s running to reclaim his Staten Island House seat.

docs.lead_paragraph: It was Staten Island reduced to an overstuffed hotel ballroom: a cannoli spread, the thick tang of hair products and undying loyalty to a man — well, two men — whom borough outsiders keep trying to tear down.

headline.print_headline: ‘Trump Guy’ Relies On Familiar Sheen In Comeback Effort

docs.abstract: Progressive women and racial minorities have toppled Democratic incumbents and eroded party machines in key states, with implications for the next Congress and the 2020 presidential race.
docs.snippet: Progressive women and racial minorities have toppled Democratic incumbents and eroded party machines in key states, with implications for the next Congress and the 2020 presidential race.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Democratic primary elections of 2018 have brought an end to an era of deference by liberals to establishment leaders in Washington and the states, as an emboldened coalition of women, young people and racial minorities claimed ownership of the party and steered it to war against President Trump.

headline.main: Democrats Embrace Liberal Insurgents, Demanding New Face for Party

docs.abstract: The battle over the confirmation of Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh has exposed a climate of partisan distrust rivaled by few other moments in the recent past.

docs.lead_paragraph: As he helped speed Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh’s embattled nomination toward a vote this week, Senator Charles E. Grassley of Iowa, the Republican chairman of the Judiciary Committee, declared that the Senate was approaching “rock bottom” and needed to right itself.

docs.abstract: The financial community is on pace to give more money to Democratic congressional candidates and incumbents than their Republican counterparts.
docs.snippet: The financial community is on pace to give more money to Democratic congressional candidates and incumbents than their Republican counterparts.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Charles Myers, the chairman of a financial advisory firm, hosted four relatively unknown Democratic congressional candidates at his Midtown Manhattan home last month, he netted more money than he can remember collecting from an event that wasn’t headlined by a presidential candidate.

headline.main: Wall Street Is Booming Under Trump. But Many of Its Donors Are Embracing Democrats.

docs.abstract: The former president, who has largely avoided campaign politics, endorsed 81 Democrats in the midterms, including officials who served in his administration.
docs.snippet: The former president, who has largely avoided campaign politics, endorsed 81 Democrats in the midterms, including officials who served in his administration.
docs.lead_paragraph: Former President Barack Obama took a public step back into the electoral arena on Wednesday, issuing a slate of 81 endorsements for Democrats running in the 2018 elections and giving his stamp of approval to more than a dozen veterans of his administration and election campaigns who are seeking office in their own right.

headline.main: Obama Endorses Dozens of Democrats, Rewarding Diversity and Loyalty

docs.abstract: Mr. Ryan’s retirement could make it easier for Democrats to win control of the House, Republicans say. The speaker had raised more than $54 million for the 2018 elections.
docs.snippet: Mr. Ryan’s retirement could make it easier for Democrats to win control of the House, Republicans say. The speaker had raised more than $54 million for the 2018 elections.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Fifteen months after Republicans took full control of Washington, the man long seen as central to the party’s future is abandoning one of the most powerful jobs in the capital, imperiling the G.O.P. grip on the House and signaling that the political convulsions of the Trump era are taking a grave toll on the right months before Election Day.

headline.main: Paul Ryan Upends Republican Hopes and Plans for Midterm Elections
headline.print_headline: Ryan Will Retire, Scattering Hopes Of G.O.P. for 2018
